<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="handoff-id-payload">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ai</group>
    <domain>ai-agents</domain>
    <summary>Handoffs are typed objects with task_id, target_agent, metadata. Receiving agent loads state from shared store. Prevents context blow-up and quadratic conversation forwarding.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>agents</tag>
      <tag>multi-agent</tag>
      <tag>handoffs</tag>
      <tag>routing</tag>
      <tag>context-management</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Handoff Payload — ID + Minimal Metadata</title>

    <summary>When agent A hands off to agent B in a multi-agent topology, the handoff payload is a structured `{task_id, target_agent, decision_metadata}` object — never the conversation history, never the raw input. Agent B reads the actual task state from a shared store (file, queue, DB) keyed by `task_id`. The supervising router returns `SupervisorDecision` objects, not message threads. Each agent's context is sized to its job, not to the cumulative conversation.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Naively forwarding the conversation between roles ("here is everything we said so far, now you handle it") is the single biggest cause of context blow-up in multi-agent systems. By turn 4, every agent in the chain is reading every prior agent's reasoning, even though most of it is irrelevant to the next role. The OpenAI Agents SDK and LangChain handoffs API both treat handoffs as structured edges with a typed payload, not as message forwarding. NERO's mesh runs on this: a classifier returns `{route: "neromedia", task_id: "t_8821"}` and the worker pulls the article body from `/srv/nero/queue/t_8821.json` — the classifier's context never carries the article at all.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Multi-agent meshes with role-specialized agents (researcher → writer → editor; classifier → worker).</item>
        <item>Supervisor/worker topologies where the supervisor's only job is routing.</item>
        <item>Long pipelines where each step's relevant context is a small subset of cumulative state.</item>
        <item>Cron-triggered or event-driven agents where the trigger has no conversation to pass on.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-agent loops — the "handoff" is a no-op; adding a store is pure overhead.</item>
        <item>Tightly-coupled co-reasoning where two agents must see each other's intermediate thoughts (use a fork/shared context instead).</item>
        <item>Throwaway prototypes where setting up a task store is more work than the agent itself.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="payload-shape">
      <p>Handoffs are typed edges, not message forwarding. The payload contains pointers and routing flags, never the original input or the prior agent's transcript.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The handoff payload from agent A to agent B MUST be a structured object with at minimum: task_id (string, key into the shared store), target_agent (string, role name), decision_metadata (object, the small set of facts B needs to plan its first action). It MUST NOT contain the raw user input, the conversation history, or A's reasoning.</statement>
        <rationale>If B needs the input, it loads from the store using task_id. Forwarding the conversation forces every agent to read the cumulative trace, which scales O(n²) in chain length.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Supervisor agents that route between workers MUST return a SupervisorDecision object (target_agent, reason, decision_metadata) as structured output — NOT a free-form message naming the next worker.</statement>
        <rationale>Free-form routing is fragile (model picks a worker name that doesn't exist, the orchestrator has to re-prompt). Structured output makes routing a typed dispatch.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Minimal payload with task_id">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[
{
  "task_id": "t_8821",
  "target_agent": "neromedia_writer",
  "decision_metadata": {
    "category": "AI",
    "lang": "uk",
    "source_count": 3
  }
}
        ]]></code>
        <note>53 bytes. Writer pulls the 3 source articles from /srv/nero/queue/t_8821.json on receipt.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Forwarding conversation history">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[
{
  "to": "neromedia_writer",
  "history": [
    {"role": "user", "content": "<6KB original article + classifier's full chain-of-thought>"}
  ]
}
        ]]></code>
        <note>The classifier's reasoning leaks into every downstream agent forever.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Passing the entire prior conversation as the handoff because "the next agent might need it".</description>
        <reason>It almost always doesn't; when it does, fetching by task_id costs the same and is reversible.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="shared-store-invariants">
      <p>The store keyed by task_id is the source of truth; agents pull from it on receipt and write back on completion.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The receiving agent MUST load task state from the shared store on first action — not from the handoff payload. The payload's decision_metadata is for routing decisions only, not for reconstructing inputs.</statement>
        <rationale>Single source of truth. If the metadata and the store disagree, the store wins; otherwise duplication causes drift between what the agent thinks the task is and what it actually is.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The store MUST expose at least three operations: get(task_id) → state, append_event(task_id, event), set_status(task_id, status). State updates MUST be append-only events, never overwrites of prior fields, so a downstream agent or a re-run can replay history.</statement>
        <rationale>Append-only state lets a failed handoff be retried without losing the prior agent's output; overwrite stores destroy evidence on retry.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Files-as-queue pattern (NERO mesh)">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# NERO mesh — files-as-queue
/srv/nero/queue/t_8821.json    # task state
/srv/nero/events/t_8821.jsonl  # append-only event log
        ]]></code>
        <note>Worker on receipt: read t_8821.json; on completion: append to events/t_8821.jsonl; supervisor: ls events/ for status.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Overwriting task state">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Worker overwrites the task state on completion
store.put(task_id, worker_output)  # prior input is gone
        ]]></code>
        <note>If a downstream editor agent fails and we want to retry, the original input is lost.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using the handoff payload as the only source of task state, with no shared store at all.</description>
        <reason>Re-runs and audit trails become impossible; the system has no memory between agents besides what was passed in the last hop.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/handoff.json" purpose="JSON Schema for the handoff payload object."/>
      <template path="templates/supervisor-decision.json" purpose="JSON Schema for the supervisor router's structured output."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/handoffs/"/>
      <link href="https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langchain/multi-agent/handoffs"/>
      <link href="https://towardsdatascience.com/how-agent-handoffs-work-in-multi-agent-systems/"/>
      <link href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/multi-agent-research-system"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
